				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\mathop \sum \limits_{i = 1}^{n} v_{i} A_{i} = \mathop \sum \limits_{j = 1}^{m} u_{i} B_{i} ,$$\end{document}with the following assumptions.

Conversion can be defined for both (semi)batch and continuous reactors as the overall conversion and instantaneous conversion. When fuel cells are used as reactors, the internal reactions are continuous [23, 43]. For continuous processes, both the overall and instantaneous conversions are the same. Furthermore, for multiple reactants, the conversion can be defined as overall or per reactant:4Xi=ni,in-ni,outni,in=1-ni,outni,in.\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
